{"response":{"status":"ok","userTier":"internal","total":95387,"startIndex":1,"pageSize":20,"currentPage":1,"pages":4770,"orderBy":"newest","tag":{"webTitle":"Books","id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},"results":[{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-11T12:08:37Z","webTitle":"Which are the best books exploring prejudice?","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/jan/11/prejudice-childrens-teen-books-racism-stereoptypes","fields":{"commentable":"false","headline":"Which are the best books exploring prejudice?","trailText":"Malorie Blackman’s racial roles reversing Noughts and Crosses made a huge impact on many readers. The book doctor searches for other books that explore stereotypes and prejudice, from Sally Green’s Half Bad to JK Rowling’s Harry Potter to Joan Lingard’s Kevin and Sadie novels","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>Can you recommend any books that raise the same issues as Malorie Blackman’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/noughts-and-crosses.html\">Noughts and Crosses</a>?</p> </blockquote> <p>Fifteen years on from its first publication, <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/noughts-and-crosses.html\">Noughts and Crosses</a> is still a stand out book for all sorts of reasons. Its power to surprise and provoke shock is just as great now as it was when it was then, perhaps even more so as global issues of racial and religious disharmony of all kinds appear to be increasing. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"00c2bfbba8ade1c38a25044f85592b83110e5a0f\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/00c2bfbba8ade1c38a25044f85592b83110e5a0f/181_0_671_1030/651.jpg\" alt=\"Noughts and crosses\" width=\"651\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Malorie Blackman’s simple reversal of racially stereotypical roles is a clever and highly effective way of focusing on the how, in any society, racism is threaded through almost every aspect of life. The dark skinned Crosses are the top group in the society, while the pale skinned Noughts are the under-class who had once been slaves. This allows Malorie Blackman to make points about the ingrained assumptions about different racial groups, without having to step carefully around current sensitivities. </p> <p>Against this background, the love story between Sephy, a dark skinned Cross and Callum, a fair skinned Nought, is agonisingly played out as the two go from the apparent ease of their permitted pre-school friendship to the distance that is bound to come between them as they grow up.</p>       <figure class=\"element element-video\" data-canonical-url=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/video/2014/jul/25/comic-con-malorie-blackman-yalc-video\"            data-short-url=\"http://gu.com/p/4v8fq\"                    data-show-ads=\"true\"            data-video-id=\"2132027\"            data-video-name=\"Malorie Blackman: my quest for diversity in children's books – video\"            data-video-provider=\"guardian.co.uk\"            data-video-poster=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/audio/video/2014/7/24/1406226298655/Comic-con---Mallory-Black-012.jpg\"> <video data-media-id=\"gu-video-442964032\" class=\"gu-video\" controls=\"controls\" poster=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/poster/2014/07/24/140725MaloryBlackman_9327537.jpg\"> <source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/mainwebsite/2014/07/25/140725MaloryBlackman-16x9.mp4\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/webM/2014/07/25/140725MaloryBlackman.webm\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/large/2014/07/25/140725MaloryBlackman_3gpLg16x9.3gp\"/><source src=\"http://cdn.theguardian.tv/3gp/small/2014/07/25/140725MaloryBlackman_3gpSml16x9.3gp\"/> </video> <figcaption>Malorie Blackman speaks to us about diversity in children’s books. </figcaption> </figure>   <p>While charting the horrible moments of disharmony, from the personal slight of the colour of a plaster to the more corrosive deliberate separations imposed by society such as segregated schools, Malorie Blackman never misses a trick in identifying the seemingly endless disadvantages of any underclass. </p> <p>But she also give hope as, first through Sephy and Callum and later through their daughter Rose in subsequent titles in the Noughts and Crosses sequence (Knife Edge, Check Mat and Double Cross), that each generation will challenge those prejudices and so gradually bring changes. There is also a <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/308554/\">graphic novel of Noughts and Crosses</a> (adapted by Ian Edginton and illustrated by John Aggs) which is not to be missed. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"4dc57a207417bececb8ec1f72e93caa5fe0f24e2\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/4dc57a207417bececb8ec1f72e93caa5fe0f24e2/0_0_309_475/309.jpg\" alt=\"Half Bad\" width=\"309\" height=\"475\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>In her series of high concept novels which begins with <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/half-bad.html\">Half Bad</a>, Sally Green explores similar issues around prejudice and stereotypical expectations. In the world she has created the polarity is between white witches and black witches (labels that don’t refer to colour, rather ‘good’ or ‘bad’). </p> <p>Both types of witches have clear characteristics and behaviour. But then a boy is born who is Half-Code; the illegitimate son of the most powerful black witch in the land he is neither one nor other. Although much less obviously a social commentary and set in a world that is far further removed from reality than Noughts and Crosses, Half Bad and its sequels <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/half-wild.html\">Half Wild</a> and Half Lost (out in March) are thought-provoking about the dangers of classifying people by their labels and not by their own characteristics and ability to think independently. Like Malorie Blackman,Sally Green gives hope that an individual can make a difference. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/apr/06/my-inspiration-sally-green-wuthering-heights-emily-bronte\">My inspiration: Sally Green on Wuthering Heights by Emily Bronte</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Also in the realms of fantasy, there are two strands of conflict one based on “blood” and the other on “belief” underlying the narrative in the JK Rowling’s Harry Potter titles; the Muggles versus the magical world and then, within the magical world, those who are followers of Voldemort and those who are not. </p> <p>Harry himself exemplifies a union between the two; he is half magical and half-Muggle and everything he does is designed to ensure that the two worlds live in harmony. </p> <p>For a very different view of the long standing prejudice against anyone with dark skin, a recent novel with a historical setting will also set readers thinking. The conditions of slaves even in a comparatively enlightened household makes horrifying reading Jon Walter’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/308920/s/my-name-s-not-friday/\">My Name’s Not Friday</a>, the story of a young boy’s experiences. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"21a860cad55bd03c0b3b2fa85dfef9112096e818\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/21a860cad55bd03c0b3b2fa85dfef9112096e818/0_0_572_842/340.jpg\" alt=\"My Name’s Not Friday\" width=\"340\" height=\"500\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Samuel becomes friends with the son of the owner of the plantation on which he is a slave but, like Sephy and Callum, their friendship is across an unbridgeable divide. Samuel is denied everything – even the right to read.</p> <p> Skin colour is not the issue in Joan Lingard’s <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/kevin-and-sadie.html\">Kevin and Sadie novels</a>. In them, she uses the very different setting of the sectarian divide in Northern Ireland in the 1960s and 1970s. </p> <p>In this case, the chasm between Kevin and Sadie is religion not race. Sadie comes from a Protestant family; Kevin’s family are Catholics. Growing up in Belfast, their religions are meant to keep them apart but, like Sephy and Callum (or Romeo and Juliet before them), the two first become friends in <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/twelfth-day-of-july.html\">The Twelfth Day of July</a>, and develop their friendship into a romance in <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/across-the-barricades.html\">Across the Barricades</a> and later, as the series continues in Into Exile, even into getting married. Joan Lingard shows that the next generation doesn’t have to adopt the engrained hatred of their parents. Instead, as in Noughts and Crosses, they can see things freshly and, especially when impelled by friendship or love, strive to change the world around them.</p> <h2><strong>If you have great recommendations on this theme let us know on Twitter <a href=\"https://twitter.com/GdnChildrensBks\">@GdnChildrensBks</a> or by emailing childrens.books@theguardian.com and we’ll add your ideas to this blog. You can use the same email address to ASK the Book Doctor a books related question.</strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fy2j","wordcount":"861","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/63fbc455c44eed995b5b79d8d67e0d1b750a0117/0_60_2400_1441/140.jpg","standfirst":"<p>Malorie Blackman’s racial roles reversing Noughts and Crosses made a huge impact on many readers. 