is.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/series/children-s-book-doctor","webTitle":"Children's book doctor","description":"Julia Eccleshare opens her surgery to all kinds of questions about reading for youngsters, and prescribes solutions. Please submit your questions to <a href=\"mailto:books@guardian.co.uk\">books@guardian.co.uk</a> ","type":"series","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/children-s-book-doctor","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/children-s-book-doctor","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/series/the-book-doctor","webTitle":"The book doctor","description":"Got a question about children's books? Email childrens.books@<br>guardian.co.uk and our book doctor, <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/profile/juliaeccleshare\">Julia Eccleshare</a> will attempt to answer it here","type":"series","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/series/the-book-doctor","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/series/the-book-doctor","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/harrypotter","webTitle":"Harry Potter","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/harrypotter","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/harrypotter","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/jkrowling","webTitle":"JK Rowling","type":"keyword","sectionId":"books","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/jkrowling","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/jkrowling","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"education/raceineducation","webTitle":"Race in education","type":"keyword","sectionId":"education","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/education/raceineducation","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/education/raceineducation","sectionName":"Education","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-11T12:00:05Z","webTitle":"The Light That Gets Lost by Natasha Carthew – review","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/jan/11/light-that-gets-lost-natasha-carthew-review","fields":{"commentable":"false","byline":"HorseLover3000","headline":"The Light That Gets Lost by Natasha Carthew – review","trailText":"<strong>HorseLover3000:</strong> ‘The story is told in an unusual, flowing style’","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>The Light That Gets Lost tells the tale of Trey, a teenage boy determined to get revenge upon his parent’s murderer, who can focus on nothing else besides. Written by Natasha Carthew, the story follows Trey on his desperate quest for vengeance, and begins as he finds himself in a camp for young offenders, where he knows his parents’ killer works.</p> <p>The story is told in an unusual, flowing style with little punctuation which makes it seem more like a train of thoughts than a coherent telling of a tale. The style is also rather lyrical, which shows off Carthew’s talent for all encompassing description; at times, however, this leaves room for little else. Carthew’s grasp and description of emotions within the book is brilliant and definitely ensures the reader understands how Trey is feeling, as it is told from his perspective.</p> <p>The downside of this author’s style is that I was often left feeling as if I didn’t completely understand where the characters were, or what was going on and why. So much of the writing is focused on emotions that the other essential aspects of a story often fell a bit flat. In particular I found the characters difficult to identify or empathise with; perhaps this is because I have never been in a young offenders camp or anything remotely similar to their situation. </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814/6_6_205_316/205.jpg\" alt=\"light that gets lost\" width=\"205\" height=\"316\" class=\"gu-image\" /> </figure>  <p>Carthew still describes her characters brilliantly, however often she seems to tell the reader things rather than show them. For example, the only leading female character in the book, Kay, is repeatedly described as wild however never do we see this wildness in action, we merely have to take Trey’s word for it. So, because of this, the characters seemed very two dimensional to me, and I never really became attached to them. Hence, when events that should have been massively significant in the story occurred, I found myself hardly bothered.</p> <p>Another part of the book I struggled to comprehend was the passage of time; I couldn’t work out how long the characters spent anyway doing anything, which isn’t something I usually notice in a story. I certainly noticed the lack of it in Light That Gets Lost. </p> <p>There is a possibility that this two dimensional grasp of the world is because the story is told from the point of view of Trey and his life revolves around revenge, however if this was the point I think it passed over my head.</p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">How do I get involved in the Guardian children's books site?</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Overall I would rate The Light That Gets Lost 4/10, and recommend it to teenage boy readers, or someone who is looking for a new style of writing to try.</p> <ul> <li><strong>Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/274769/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></li> </ul> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read?<a href=\"http://preview.gutools.co.uk/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ffpj","wordcount":"473","standfirst":"<p>‘The story is told in an unusual, flowing style’</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/11/light-that-gets-lost-natasha-carthew-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/11/light-that-gets-lost-natasha-carthew-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814/6_6_205_316/205.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814","altText":"light that gets lost","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814/6_6_205_316/205.jpg","width":"205","height":"316"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814/6_6_205_316/master/205.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814","altText":"light that gets lost","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/b4b6e42adcfe9b1246ad70f23571074c8d89f814/6_6_205_316/master/205.jpg","width":"205","height":"316","isMaster":"true"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]},{"id":"_no_ids","relation":"body","type":"embed","assets":[{"type":"embed","file":"http://www.theguardian.com