 a Jewish doctor, and Konradin, scion of a noted aristocratic family. Both have a passionate interest in history, and against the odds – snobbery is rife in their ultra-competitive school – this brings them together.</p> <p>But their beloved Germany is changing. Sides will have to be taken, loyalties adhered to. Disgust, rejection, fear, exile, stoicism, bravery: these are the things the years ahead will bring, even if their pattern will not be fully revealed for many decades. Uhlman’s story, which takes on the most terrible crime of the 20th century, could easily have wound up a fable, pat and sentimental. Somehow, though, it never comes close to being so, perhaps because he is careful not to lose sight of the bonds from which its beginning is forged. A daring miracle of narrative simplicity, its end comes at you like a torch in a long tunnel. All is black, calamitously beyond words, and yet the eye, swiftly followed by the heart, is drawn to it: at last, a circle of light. Even if history cannot be rewritten, Uhlman tells us, a life may sometimes have more than one act.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4ffnp","wordcount":"327","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/ac58157b27ed65b4cd02e3ce4e71939d5eefcc42/0_164_2104_1262/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-31T00:00:00Z","standfirst":"Set in 1930s Germany, Fred Uhlman’s novella Reunion is a simple story of friendship in not so simple times"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/jan/11/fred-uhlman-reunion-epic-tale","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/jan/11/fred-uhlman-reunion-epic-tale","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"ac58157b27ed65b4cd02e3ce4e71939d5eefcc42","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/ac58157b27ed65b4cd02e3ce4e71939d5eefcc42/0_164_2104_1262/2000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/ac58157b27ed65b4cd02e3ce4e71939d5eefcc42","altText":"Fred Uhlman, the Germa