senting culture videos. A new edition of his <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2009/apr/04/rough-guide-shakespeare-andrew-dickson\">Rough Guide to Shakespeare</a> came out in 2009, he has contributed to the New Cambridge Companion to Shakespeare (2010), and he appears regularly as a critic for the BBC.  He is also an honorary fellow in the <a href=\"http://www.bbk.ac.uk/english/\">English department of Birkbeck College</a>, University of London. He blogs at <a href=\"http://worldselsewhere.com\">worldselsewhere.com</a>.</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/andrewdickson","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/andrewdickson","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/g2","webTitle":"G2","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/g2","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/g2/features11","webTitle":"G2 Comment & features","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"theguardian","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/g2/features11","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/g2/features11","sectionName":"From the Guardian","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-10T17:30:00Z","webTitle":"‘Just 1,238 pages to go’: could you read War and Peace in a week?","sectionId":"tv-and-radio","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"tv-and-radio/2016/jan/10/just-1238-pages-to-go-could-you-read-war-and-peace-in-a-week","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Tim Dowling","headline":"‘Just 1,238 pages to go’: could you read War and Peace in a week?","trailText":"The BBC is screening a lavish adaptation of Tolstoy’s epic novel over six weeks. So Tim Dowling tried to read it in just one. Could he finish it in time for the next instalment?<br>","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>My wife and I are watching the first episode of the BBC adaptation of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/jan/04/war-and-peace-deutschland-83-review\">War and Peace</a> in silence. Fifteen minutes in, I am afraid to say what I am thinking, which is: I am confused. Who are these people? How are they connected? What are they talking about? I am determined not to speak first.</p> <p>“I don’t remember any of this,” my wife says. I nod, and then I think: remember it from when? Something occurs to me.</p> <p>“Have you read <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/oct/08/classics.leonikolaevichtolstoy\">War and Peace</a>?” I say.</p> <p>“Of course,” she says. “I skipped all the war bits.”</p> <p>I have not read War and Peace, and I am so unacquainted with the story that I have little idea of what I am missing. I know it concerns (among other things, I’m guessing) the Napoleonic wars, and I know it is long. I have committed it, along with several other titles, to a mental list labelled Great Works to Save For a Future Time When You Are Bedridden.</p> <p>But before episode one is finished, I have decided that I am going to read War and Peace. I imagine myself sitting down to episode two armed with more background than my wife could hope to command. I will answer her befuddled queries by saying: “That is Count So-and-so who, you will no doubt recall, is promised to young Princess Whatshername, though their families are against it.” I will not skip the war bits. I’m not a particularly fast reader, but who cares? I have a whole week.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"da42aae2395a003fb9b68cdcb787fda6cbea7dca\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/da42aae2395a003fb9b68cdcb787fda6cbea7dca/65_0_1867_2800/667.jpg\" alt=\"It’s a classic …\" width=\"667\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">It’s a classic …</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Alamy</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <h2><strong>Day one</strong></h2> <p>After scanning our bookshelves in vain the next morning, I approach my wife at her desk.</p> <p>“Do we actually have a copy of War and Peace?” I say.</p> <p>“What for?” she says.</p> <p>“No reason,” I say.</p> <p>“We do somewhere,” she says, turning to stare at the bookshelves behind her. “It’s red and secondhand, and I don’t know when I last saw it. It could be absolutely … Oh, there it is.” She pulls an unassuming old hardback off a high shelf and hands it to me.</p> <p>“This doesn’t look too daunting,” I say, surreptitiously opening it from the back to look at the last page number: 428.</p> <p>“That’s volume one of three,” she says, handing me two more books. I take the stack up to my office, open volume one, skip the introduction and begin reading page one.</p> <p>Fifteen minutes later, I am still on page one. There is something about the opening – a lengthy, uninterrupted chunk of speech – that will not sink in: “Well, prince, what did I tell you? Genoa and Lucca have become the property of the Bonapartes. Now, I give you fair warning, you will forfeit your position as my friend – as my faithful slave, as you choose to say – if you persist in disbelieving in war, and are still determined to defend all the horrors and atrocities perpetrated by this Antichrist – for that he is Antichrist I am convinced …” There is more, but you get the idea. It takes a bit of nerve, I think, to start a novel with a lengthy quotation from an as yet unidentified speaker, unless you mean to try the reader’s patience from the outset.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--showcase\" data-media-id=\"f285aefeeaf7b665d4c6dae347f543364ec8d6a0\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/f285aefeeaf7b665d4c6dae347f543364ec8d6a0/0_0_4080_2449/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Who are all these people and why do their names keep changing?\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Who are all these people and why do their names keep changing?</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Mitch Jenkins/PR</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>An hour later I am on page 12, and I know the speaker of that opening paragraph to be Anna Paulovna Scherer, aka Gillian Anderson. But that is about all I know. Old familiar questions surface: Who are these people? How are they connected? What are they talking about? After a while I have to put the book down to get on with other things. I can’t just lie about reading all day like some bespectacled Russian aristocrat. When I turn out my bedside light that night, I am on page 23. Just 1,238 pages to go.</p> <h2><strong>Day two</strong></h2> <p>My confusion as to who is whom has subsided but a little. It’s not just that there are so many characters, but that they each have so many names. Along with a first name and a family name, a character may also possess a diminutive, a patronymic, a title and possibly a military rank. They are addressed variously, depending on who they are talking to. So Princess Drubetskaya is Anna Mikhaylovna to her friends. The Rostov family has two Natalias, who both also answer to Natasha, one of whom is also Countess Rostov, or just the Countess.</p> <p>My copy of the book – the 1949 Everyman’s Library edition – makes things worse. A publisher’s note says it is based on the so-called “anonymous” 1886 translation which, I gather, was originally translated into English from a French translation. The main problem is that the names are not rendered in the modern fashion. “Bezukhov” is spelled “Besoukhow”. Prince Vassily is known, from page one, as Prince Basil.</p> <p>Wikipedia offers a fairly comprehensive list of characters, but most descriptions also include a terrible spoiler: “Had an affair with Natasha Rostov”; “later loses an arm”.</p> <p>When it comes to keeping things straight, I find I am entirely reliant on the BBC adaptation. Once I can identify a character as, say, Rebecca Front, I can assign all five of her names to one face.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"76ed17c5ad62ae5dd842c847c4224d3d794d6e29\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/76ed17c5ad62ae5dd842c847c4224d3d794d6e29/0_141_4291_2576/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Gripping … the battle scenes are impossible to skip.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Gripping … the battle scenes are impossible to skip.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Robert Viglasky/BBC/Robert Viglasky</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>I read on the tube in the morning. In the afternoon, I fall asleep on the sofa with the book on my face. I finish the day on page 78. So far there have been no war bits to skip.</p> <h2><strong>Day three</strong></h2> <p>I am reliably informed by a colleague who has read War and Peace that I need not bother with Tolstoy’s 100-odd page digression on the nature of freemasonry. That sounds an awfully long way away. After three days I still haven’t covered all the events that occur in episode one of the TV version. But it is always heartening to recognise a scene from the dramatisation: the death of old Count Bezukhov; Andrei Bolkonsky’s leave-taking; giddiness in the Rostov’s drawing room.</p> <p>For the moment, however, I can leave the drawing rooms behind. At last, we are at war. This part is confusing in a whole new way. Titles and ranks are used interchangeably by the narrator. Aide-de-camps gather in shoals in anterooms, one indistinguishable from the other. New characters arrive with every turn of the page. Come on, I keep thinking – let’s get the fighting started, and thin the field out a little.</p> <p>My edition has almost no footnotes, so I read with my phone at my elbow, in case I feel that I need to know what is meant by “a native of Little Russia” (a Ukrainian, basically), but mostly I just push on, blinkered by ignorance. More knowledge would only slow my pace. I am sure it will all make sense in the end.</p> <p>“Are you still reading War and Peace?” says my youngest son, finding me hunched over the book in the kitchen.</p> <p>“What do you mean, still?” I say.</p> <p>“You know it’s on TV, right?”</p> <p>“Yes, that’s the whole … never mind.”</p> <p>I finally put down the book just after midnight, on page 186. The type is tiny, by the way. Did I mention that?</p> <h2><strong>Day four</strong></h2> <p>Battle, when it finally comes, is gripping. I can’t imagine skipping this part. What is commonly referred to as the Fog of War is here, rendered in all its terrifying confusion. Even success on the battlefield happens by accident, when orders are delivered and the battery commanded by Tushin fails to retreat. The experiences of Nicholas Rostov are particularly vivid, because I saw them on TV quite recently.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"450d0178ddcf306beca28fe01091598bb45b9eb8\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/450d0178ddcf306beca28fe01091598bb45b9eb8/0_418_7360_4415/1000.jpg\" alt=\"I’ll get there in the end …\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">I’ll get there in the end …</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Linda Nylind for the Guardian</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>By now I feel I have caught the rhythm of the novel, and developed an instinct for knowing when a character is not going to trouble me again, so I needn’t worry too much about his rank or nickname. I now find myself back in St Petersburg, and I have been away just long enough to forget who everyone is. Some 230 pages in, I realise with a start that Helene Kuragina is actually the daughter of the person I have been calling Prince Basil. I am sure I was meant to know this earlier. When I go back to consult the TV version, I see this was made clear in the first three minutes. Every page I read from now on is uncharted territory, at least until episode two airs.</p> <p>I’m already one sixth of the way through War and Peace; with luck and a fair wind, I figure I can beat the six-part TV adaptation by a week. And when at some point in the future I find myself bedridden, I can just watch old episodes of Celebrity Antiques Road Trip. I will have earned it.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fjzd","wordcount":"1457","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/f4bbd8e3e2e5344b4bb8a68da8bc388eac7713ee/0_330_7360_4415/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-13T17:30:00Z","standfirst":"<p>The BBC is screening a lavish adaptation of Tolstoy’s epic novel over six weeks. So Tim Dowling tried to read it in just one. Could he finish it in time for the next instalment?<br></p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/jan/10/just-1238-pages-to-go-could-you-read-war-and-peace-in-a-week","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/2016/jan/10/just-1238-pages-to-go-could-you-read-war-and-peace-in-a-week","sectionName":"Television & radio","elements":[{"id":"f4bbd8e3e2e5344b4bb8a68da8bc388eac7713ee","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/f4bbd8e3e2e5344b4bb8a68da8bc388eac7713ee/0_330_7360_4415/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"Linda Nylind","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/f4bbd8e3e2e5344b4bb8a68da8bc388eac7713ee","altText":"Now that I’ve got past that tricky first page … Dowling battles with Tolstoy’s epic.","caption":"Now that I’ve got past that tricky first page … Dowling battles with Tolstoy’s epic.","photographer":"Linda Nylind","source":"The Guardian","credit":"Photograph: Linda Nylind for the Guardian","mediaId":"f4bbd8e3e2e5344b4bb8a68da8bc388eac77